[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] At a basic level, test functions request fixtures they require by declaring them as arguments.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] When pytest goes to run a test, it looks at the parameters in that test function’s signature, and then searches for fixtures that have the same names as those parameters.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Once pytest finds them, it runs those fixtures, captures what they returned (if anything), and passes those objects into the test function as arguments.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] In this example, `test_fruit_salad` “**requests**” `fruit_bowl` (i.e.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] `def test_fruit_salad(fruit_bowl):`), and when pytest sees this, it will execute the `fruit_bowl` fixture function and pass the object it returns into `test_fruit_salad` as the `fruit_bowl` argument.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] One of pytest’s greatest strengths is its extremely flexible fixture system.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] It allows us to boil down complex requirements for tests into more simple and organized functions, where we only need to have each one describe the things they are dependent on.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Notice that this is the same example from above, but very little changed.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The fixtures in pytest **request** fixtures just like tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] All the same **requesting** rules apply to fixtures that do for tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] One of the things that makes pytest’s fixture system so powerful, is that it gives us the ability to define a generic setup step that can be reused over and over, just like a normal function would be used.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Two different tests can request the same fixture and have pytest give each test their own result from that fixture.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This is extremely useful for making sure tests aren’t affected by each other.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] We can use this system to make sure each test gets its own fresh batch of data and is starting from a clean state so it can provide consistent, repeatable results.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Each test here is being given its own copy of that `list` object, which means the `order` fixture is getting executed twice (the same is true for the `first_entry` fixture).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Tests and fixtures aren’t limited to **requesting** a single fixture at a time.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Fixtures can also be **requested** more than once during the same test, and pytest won’t execute them again for that test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This means we can **request** fixtures in multiple fixtures that are dependent on them (and even again in the test itself) without those fixtures being executed more than once.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] If a **requested** fixture was executed once for every time it was **requested** during a test, then this test would fail because both `append_first` and `test_string_only` would see `order` as an empty list (i.e.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] `[]`), but since the return value of `order` was cached (along with any side effects executing it may have had) after the first time it was called, both the test and `append_first` were referencing the same object, and the test saw the effect `append_first` had on that object.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Sometimes you may want to have a fixture (or even several) that you know all your tests will depend on. “Autouse” fixtures are a convenient way to make all tests automatically **request** them.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This can cut out a lot of redundant **requests**, and can even provide more advanced fixture usage (more on that further down).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] We can make a fixture an autouse fixture by passing in `autouse=True` to the fixture’s decorator.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] In this example, the `append_first` fixture is an autouse fixture.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Because it happens automatically, both tests are affected by it, even though neither test **requested** it.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] That doesn’t mean they *can’t* be **requested** though; just that it isn’t *necessary*.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Fixtures requiring network access depend on connectivity and are usually time-expensive to create.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Multiple test functions in a test module will thus each receive the same `smtp_connection` fixture instance, thus saving time.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Possible values for `scope` are: `function`, `class`, `module`, `package` or `session`.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Here, the `test_ehlo` needs the `smtp_connection` fixture value. pytest will discover and call the `@pytest.fixture` marked `smtp_connection` fixture function.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] You see the two `assert 0` failing and more importantly you can also see that the **exact same** `smtp_connection` object was passed into the two test functions because pytest shows the incoming argument values in the traceback.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] As a result, the two test functions using `smtp_connection` run as quick as a single one because they reuse the same instance.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Pytest only caches one instance of a fixture at a time, which means that when using a parametrized fixture, pytest may invoke a fixture more than once in the given scope.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] In some cases, you might want to change the scope of the fixture without changing the code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The callable must return a string with a valid scope and will be executed only once - during the fixture definition.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] It will be called with two keyword arguments - `fixture_name` as a string and `config` with a configuration object.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This can be especially useful when dealing with fixtures that need time for setup, like spawning a docker container.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] You can use the command-line argument to control the scope of the spawned containers for different environments.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] When we run our tests, we’ll want to make sure they clean up after themselves so they don’t mess with any other tests (and also so that we don’t leave behind a mountain of test data to bloat the system).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Fixtures in pytest offer a very useful teardown system, which allows us to define the specific steps necessary for each fixture to clean up after itself.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This system can be leveraged in two ways.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] “Yield” fixtures `yield` instead of `return`.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] With these fixtures, we can run some code and pass an object back to the requesting fixture/test, just like with the other fixtures.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Any teardown code for that fixture is placed *after* the `yield`.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Once pytest figures out a linear order for the fixtures, it will run each one up until it returns or yields, and then move on to the next fixture in the list to do the same thing.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Once the test is finished, pytest will go back down the list of fixtures, but in the *reverse order*, taking each one that yielded, and running the code inside it that was *after* the `yield` statement.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Let’s say we want to test sending email from one user to another.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] We’ll have to first make each user, then send the email from one user to the other, and finally assert that the other user received that message in their inbox.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] If we want to clean up after the test runs, we’ll likely have to make sure the other user’s mailbox is emptied before deleting that user, otherwise the system may complain.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Because `receiving_user` is the last fixture to run during setup, it’s the first to run during teardown.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] There is a risk that even having the order right on the teardown side of things doesn’t guarantee a safe cleanup.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] That’s covered in a bit more detail in Safe teardowns.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] If a yield fixture raises an exception before yielding, pytest won’t try to run the teardown code after that yield fixture’s `yield` statement.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] But, for every fixture that has already run successfully for that test, pytest will still attempt to tear them down as it normally would.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] While yield fixtures are considered to be the cleaner and more straightforward option, there is another choice, and that is to add “finalizer” functions directly to the test’s request-context object.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] It brings a similar result as yield fixtures, but requires a bit more verbosity.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] In order to use this approach, we have to request the request-context object (just like we would request another fixture) in the fixture we need to add teardown code for, and then pass a callable, containing that teardown code, to its `addfinalizer` method.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] We have to be careful though, because pytest will run that finalizer once it’s been added, even if that fixture raises an exception after adding the finalizer.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] So to make sure we don’t run the finalizer code when we wouldn’t need to, we would only add the finalizer once the fixture would have done something that we’d need to teardown.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] It’s a bit longer than yield fixtures and a bit more complex, but it does offer some nuances for when you’re in a pinch.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Finalizers are executed in a first-in-last-out order.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] For yield fixtures, the first teardown code to run is from the right-most fixture, i.e. the last test parameter.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] For finalizers, the first fixture to run is last call to `request.addfinalizer`.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This is so because yield fixtures use `addfinalizer` behind the scenes: when the fixture executes, `addfinalizer` registers a function that resumes the generator, which in turn calls the teardown code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The fixture system of pytest is *very* powerful, but it’s still being run by a computer, so it isn’t able to figure out how to safely teardown everything we throw at it.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] If we aren’t careful, an error in the wrong spot might leave stuff from our tests behind, and that can cause further issues pretty quickly.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This version is a lot more compact, but it’s also harder to read, doesn’t have a very descriptive fixture name, and none of the fixtures can be reused easily.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] There’s also a more serious issue, which is that if any of those steps in the setup raise an exception, none of the teardown code will run.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] One option might be to go with the `addfinalizer` method instead of yield fixtures, but that might get pretty complex and difficult to maintain (and it wouldn’t be compact anymore).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The safest and simplest fixture structure requires limiting fixtures to only making one state-changing action each, and then bundling them together with their teardown code, as the email examples above showed.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The chance that a state-changing operation can fail but still modify state is negligible, as most of these operations tend to be transaction-based (at least at the level of testing where state could be left behind).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] So if we make sure that any successful state-changing action gets torn down by moving it to a separate fixture function and separating it from other, potentially failing state-changing actions, then our tests will stand the best chance at leaving the test environment the way they found it.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] For an example, let’s say we have a website with a login page, and we have access to an admin API where we can generate users.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] We wouldn’t want to leave that user in the system, nor would we want to leave that browser session running, so we’ll want to make sure the fixtures that create those things clean up after themselves.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] For this example, certain fixtures (i.e.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] `base_url` and `admin_credentials`) are implied to exist elsewhere.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] So for now, let’s assume they exist, and we’re just not looking at them.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The way the dependencies are laid out means it’s unclear if the `user` fixture would execute before the `driver` fixture.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] But that’s ok, because those are atomic operations, and so it doesn’t matter which one runs first because the sequence of events for the test is still linearizable.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] But what *does* matter is that, no matter which one runs first, if the one raises an exception while the other would not have, neither will have left anything behind.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] If `driver` executes before `user`, and `user` raises an exception, the driver will still quit, and the user was never made.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] And if `driver` was the one to raise the exception, then the driver would never have been started and the user would never have been made.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Sometimes you may want to run multiple asserts after doing all that setup, which makes sense as, in more complex systems, a single action can kick off multiple behaviors. pytest has a convenient way of handling this and it combines a bunch of what we’ve gone over so far.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] All that’s needed is stepping up to a larger scope, then having the **act** step defined as an autouse fixture, and finally, making sure all the fixtures are targeting that higher level scope.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Let’s pull an example from above, and tweak it a bit.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Let’s say that in addition to checking for a welcome message in the header, we also want to check for a sign out button, and a link to the user’s profile.
