[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] No state is tied to the actual test class as it might be in the `unittest.TestCase` framework.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Everything is managed by the pytest fixture system.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] Each method only has to request the fixtures that it actually needs without worrying about order.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] This is because the **act** fixture is an autouse fixture, and it made sure all the other fixtures executed before it.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] There’s no more changes of state that need to take place, so the tests are free to make as many non-state-changing queries as they want without risking stepping on the toes of the other tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/fixtures-p01] The `login` fixture is defined inside the class as well, because not every one of the other tests in the module will be expecting a successful login, and the **act** may need to be handled a little differently for another test class.
