[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-double] A *verified fake* is a fake object whose behavior has been verified to match that of the real object using a set of tests that run against both the verified fake and the real implementation.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] A **test fixture** is a device used to consistently test some item, device, or piece of software.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures are used in the testing of electronics, software and physical devices.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In testing electronic equipment such as circuit boards, electronic components, and chips, a test fixture is a device or setup designed to hold the device under test in place and allow it to be tested by being subjected to controlled electronic test signals.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Examples are a bed of nails tester or smart fixture.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures can come in different shapes, sizes, and functions.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] There are several different types of test fixtures, including In-Circuit Test Fixtures, Functional Test Fixtures, and Wireless Test Fixtures.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In Circuit Test (ICT) fixtures individually test each component on a PCB, while functional test fixtures assess the entire board's functionality.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Functional test fixtures simulate real-world conditions, whereas ICT is more focused on detecting assembly defects like short circuits or missing components.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] An In-Circuit Test fixture can come in both Inline and Standard variations.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] An Inline Test Fixture is designed for fast, automated testing directly within a production line, ideal for high-volume manufacturing where continuous testing maximises efficiency.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] A Standard Test Fixture, on the other hand, usually requires manual loading, making it well-suited to smaller-scale or specialised testing.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In the context of software, a test fixture (also called "test context") is used to set up the system state and input data needed for test execution.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] For example, the Ruby on Rails web framework uses YAML to initialize a database with known parameters before running a test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] This allows for tests to be repeatable, which is one of the key features of an effective test framework.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In most cases, a custom test fixture will normally require custom test software.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] This software is created in order to ensure optimal testing performance and seamless integration.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] The custom software can be configured to carry out a number of different tests from BIST (Built-In Self Test) to advanced JTAG Implementation.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures can be set up three different ways: in-line, delegate, and implicit.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Delegate setup places the test fixture in a separate standalone helper method that is accessed by multiple test methods.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Implicit setup places the test fixture in a setup method which is used to set up multiple test methods.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] This differs from delegate setup in that the overall setup of multiple tests is in a single setup method where the test fixture gets created rather than each test method having its own setup procedures and linking to an external test fixture.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] The main advantage of a test fixture is that it allows for tests to be repeatable since each test is always starting with the same setup.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures also ease test code design by allowing the developer to separate methods into different functions and reuse each function for other tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Further, test fixtures preconfigure tests into a known initial state instead of working with whatever was left from a previous test run.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] A disadvantage is that it could lead to duplication of test fixtures if using in-line setup.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] It is considered bad practice when implicit test fixtures are too general, or when a test method sets up a test fixture and does not use it during the test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] A more subtle issue is if the test methods ignore certain fields within the test fixture.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Another bad practice is a test setup that contains more steps than needed for the test; this is a problem seen in in-line setup.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] A test case is considered "unsafe" when it modifies its fixture(s).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] An unsafe test case can render subsequent tests useless by leaving the fixture in an unexpected state.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] It also causes the order of tests to be important: a modified fixture must be reset if more tests are to be run after an unsafe test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Examples of fixtures include loading a database with a specific known set of data, erasing a hard disk and installing a known clean operating system installation, copying a specific known set of files, or the preparation of input data as well as set-up and creation of mock objects.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Software which is used to run reproducible tests systematically on a piece of software under test is known as a test harness; part of its job is to set up suitable test fixtures.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In generic xUnit, a *test fixture* is all the things that must be in place in order to run a test and expect a particular outcome.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Frequently fixtures are created by handling *setUp()* and *tearDown()* events of the unit testing framework.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In *setUp()* one would create the expected state for the test and in *tearDown()* it would clean up what had been set up.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] In physical testing, a fixture is a device or apparatus to hold or support the test specimen during the test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] The influence of test fixtures on test results is important and is an ongoing subject of research.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Many test methods detail the requirements of test fixtures in the text of the document.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Some fixtures employ clamps, wedge grips and pincer grips.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Further types of construction include eccentric roller fixtures, thread grips and button head grips and rope grips.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Mechanical holding apparatuses provide the clamping force via arms, wedges or eccentric wheel to the jaws.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/test-fixture] Additionally there are pneumatic and hydraulic fixtures for tensile testing that allow very fast clamping procedures and very high clamping forces.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In C and other languages, compiler directives such as `#if DEBUG ... #endif` can be placed around such additional classes and indeed all other test-related code to prevent them being compiled into the released code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] This means the released code is not exactly the same as what was unit tested.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] The regular running of fewer but more comprehensive, end-to-end, integration tests on the final release build can ensure (among other things) that no production code exists that subtly relies on aspects of the test harness.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] There is some debate among developers, as to whether it is wise to test private methods and data anyway.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Some argue that private members are a mere implementation detail that may change, and should be allowed to do so without breaking numbers of tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Thus it should be sufficient to test any class through its public interface or through its subclass interface, which some languages call the "protected" interface.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Others say that crucial aspects of functionality may be implemented in private methods and testing them directly offers advantage of smaller and more direct unit tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written before the related production code is written.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Starting with a failing test, then adds *just enough* production code to make the test pass, then refactors the code as makes sense and then repeats by adding another failing test.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing is intended to ensure that the units meet their design and behave as intended.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] By writing tests first for the smallest testable units, then the compound behaviors between those, one can build up comprehensive tests for complex applications.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] One goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A unit test provides a strict, written contract that the piece of code must satisfy.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing finds problems early in the development cycle.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] This includes both bugs in the programmer's implementation and flaws or missing parts of the specification for the unit.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] The process of writing a thorough set of tests forces the author to think through inputs, outputs, and error conditions, and thus more crisply define the unit's desired behavior.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] The cost of finding a bug before coding begins or when the code is first written is considerably lower than the cost of detecting, identifying, and correcting the bug later.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Bugs in released code may also cause costly problems for the end-users of the software.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Code can be impossible or difficult to unit test if poorly written, thus unit testing can force developers to structure functions and objects in better ways.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing enables more frequent releases in software development.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] By testing individual components in isolation, developers can quickly identify and address issues, leading to faster iteration and release cycles.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing allows the programmer to refactor code or upgrade system libraries at a later date, and make sure the module still works correctly (e.g., in regression testing).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] The procedure is to write test cases for all functions and methods so that whenever a change causes a fault, it can be identified quickly.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit tests detect changes which may break a design contract.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing may reduce uncertainty in the units themselves and can be used in a bottom-up testing style approach.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] By testing the parts of a program first and then testing the sum of its parts, integration testing becomes much easier.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Some programmers contend that unit tests provide a form of documentation of the code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Developers wanting to learn what functionality is provided by a unit, and how to use it, can review the unit tests to gain an understanding of it.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Test cases can embody characteristics that are critical to the success of the unit.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] These characteristics can indicate appropriate/inappropriate use of a unit as well as negative behaviors that are to be trapped by the unit.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] A test case documents these critical characteristics, although many software development environments do not rely solely upon code to document the product in development.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In some processes, the act of writing tests and the code under test, plus associated refactoring, may take the place of formal design.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Each unit test can be seen as a design element specifying classes, methods, and observable behavior.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Testing will not catch every error in the program, because it cannot evaluate every execution path in any but the most trivial programs.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] This problem is a superset of the halting problem, which is undecidable.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Additionally, unit testing by definition only tests the functionality of the units themselves.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Therefore, it will not catch integration errors or broader system-level errors (such as functions performed across multiple units, or non-functional test areas such as performance).
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing should be done in conjunction with other software testing activities, as they can only show the presence or absence of particular errors; they cannot prove a complete absence of errors.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] To guarantee correct behavior for every execution path and every possible input, and ensure the absence of errors, other techniques are required, namely the application of formal methods to prove that a software component has no unexpected behavior.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] An elaborate hierarchy of unit tests does not equal integration testing.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Integration with peripheral units should be included in integration tests, but not in unit tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Integration testing typically still relies heavily on humans testing manually; high-level or global-scope testing can be difficult to automate, such that manual testing often appears faster and cheaper.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Software testing is a combinatorial problem.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] For example, every Boolean decision statement requires at least two tests: one with an outcome of "true" and one with an outcome of "false".
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] As a result, for every line of code written, programmers often need 3 to 5 lines of test code.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] This obviously takes time and its investment may not be worth the effort.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] There are problems that cannot easily be tested at all – for example those that are nondeterministic or involve multiple threads.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] In addition, code for a unit test is as likely to be buggy as the code it is testing.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Another challenge related to writing the unit tests is the difficulty of setting up realistic and useful tests.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] It is necessary to create relevant initial conditions so the part of the application being tested behaves like part of the complete system.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] If these initial conditions are not set correctly, the test will not be exercising the code in a realistic context, which diminishes the value and accuracy of unit test results.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] To obtain the intended benefits from unit testing, rigorous discipline is needed throughout the software development process.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] It is essential to keep careful records not only of the tests that have been performed, but also of all changes that have been made to the source code of this or any other unit in the software.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] Use of a version control system is essential.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] If a later version of the unit fails a particular test that it had previously passed, the version-control software can provide a list of the source code changes (if any) that have been applied to the unit since that time.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] It is also essential to implement a sustainable process for ensuring that test case failures are reviewed regularly and addressed immediately.
[src:pytest-fixtures-lib/unit-testing] If such a process is not implemented and ingrained into the team's workflow, the application will evolve out of sync with the unit test suite, increasing false positives and reducing the effectiveness of the test suite.
